Based on the provided operational reports, I've crafted an ontology that captures key concepts, their relationships, and categories. Here's a JSON-like format for easy interpretation and computational use:

```json
{
  "Event": {
    "name": "Flooding",
    "type": "Disaster",
    "location": {
      "name": "Ahr Valley",
      "subregions": ["Rech", "Bad Neuenahr", "Dernau", "Ahrbrück"]
    },
    "date": "July 2021"
  },
  "Responders": {
    "fire_brigade": {
      "units": [
        "LE 03 - Vettelschoß",
        "FEZ Linz",
        "FW Leubsdorf",
        "FW Linz am Rhein",
        "FW St. Katharinen"
      ],
      "roles": ["first_disaster_control", "rescue_and_supply", "clearing_paths"]
    },
    "other_responders": [
      "THW (Technisches Hilfswerk)",
      "Bundeswehr",
      "police",
      "rescue services"
    ]
  },
  "Tasks": {
    "rescue": ["evacuation", "search_and_rescue"],
    "support": ["supplying_residents_with_goods", "providing_hygiene_services"],
    "clearing": ["removing_blockages", "opening_access_routes"]
  },
  "Impact": {
    "structural_damage": ["destroyed_houses", "collapsed_bridges"],
    "infrastructure_loss": ["no_electricity", "no_drinking_water", "no_telephone_lines"],
    "human_suffering": ["despair", "hope", "great_gratitude"]
  },
  "Organizations": {
    "local_authorities": "Ahrweiler district",
    "media_outlets": ["SWR television", "Rheinzeitung", "Generalanzeiger Bonn"]
  }
}
```

This ontology captures the main entities involved in the disaster event (e.g., responders, tasks, impact), their relationships (e.g., fire_brigade units performing rescue tasks), and categories (e.g., responder types, task types). This structure can be easily extended to include more information from similar reports or other sources.